INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '6b1ccb15-93de-4e4f-926e-bb2e3502bdf6',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Polars Lazy API — Why collect() Is the Only Line That Costs You$escape$,
  $escape$Polars' lazy evaluation rewrites your entire query plan before touching a single row. When you call .lazy(), nothing executes — Polars builds a logical plan. Calling .collect() triggers the optimizer: predicate pushdown filters rows before joins, projection pushdown drops unused columns, and common subexpression elimination deduplicates work. This is why a chained lazy pipeline often outperforms the equivalent eager Pandas code by 5–20x on datasets over 1M rows.

The expressions API is the key differentiator. Instead of row-wise apply(), Polars expressions like pl.col('price').over('category').mean() compile to vectorized, multi-threaded operations on Arrow-backed columns. No GIL, no copies.

When to switch from Pandas: if you're calling .apply() with a Python lambda on more than 100K rows, if you're chaining multiple groupby-aggregations, or if memory pressure forces you to process in chunks. Polars handles all three natively — streaming mode even processes larger-than-RAM datasets lazily.$escape$,
  $escape$import polars as pl

df = pl.scan_parquet("events.parquet")  # returns LazyFrame

result = (
    df
    .filter(pl.col("status") == "completed")
    .with_columns(
        pl.col("revenue").over("region").mean().alias("avg_region_rev")
    )
    .group_by("region")
    .agg(
        pl.col("revenue").sum().alias("total"),
        pl.col("user_id").n_unique().alias("unique_users"),
    )
    .sort("total", descending=True)
    .collect()  # optimizer runs here
)$escape$,
  $escape$python$escape$,
