INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'cb720a53-4411-49c8-87e6-82c72c6ed696',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Polars for Statistical Testing — Hypothesis Tests Without Leaving Your DataFrame$escape$,
  $escape$Polars doesn't ship scipy, but its expression engine handles the heavy lifting of preparing statistical tests efficiently. Compute group means, variances, and sample sizes in a single lazy query, then pass results to scipy for the final p-value. The key advantage: Polars computes aggregations in parallel across groups before you ever touch Python-speed code.

For confidence intervals, use `col.mean()`, `col.std()`, and `col.count()` expressions to build margin-of-error calculations directly. With `group_by().agg()`, you can compute test statistics for hundreds of A/B segments in one pass — no loops, no apply.

When p-values matter: feature drift detection, A/B tests on model predictions, validating that a retrained model's error distribution hasn't shifted. When they don't: exploratory slicing where effect sizes speak for themselves.

Pro tip: use `.with_columns()` to attach confidence bounds directly to summary frames, keeping everything in a single Polars pipeline instead of juggling numpy arrays.$escape$,
  $escape$import polars as pl
from scipy import stats

df = pl.DataFrame({"group": ["A"]*100 + ["B"]*100, "value": range(200)})

summary = df.group_by("group").agg(
    mean=pl.col("value").mean(),
    std=pl.col("value").std(),
    n=pl.col("value").count(),
).with_columns(
    ci_95=(1.96 * pl.col("std") / pl.col("n").sqrt()).alias("ci_95"),
)

rows = summary.sort("group").to_dicts()
t_stat, p_value = stats.ttest_ind_from_stats(
    rows[0]["mean"], rows[0]["std"], rows[0]["n"],
    rows[1]["mean"], rows[1]["std"], rows[1]["n"],
)
print(f"t={t_stat:.3f}, p={p_value:.4f}")$escape$,
  $escape$python$escape$,
