INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '2a7d5f70-5a50-4019-97f1-054b52a271bd',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Polars to Plot — Visualization Best Practices Without the Chartjunk$escape$,
  $escape$Polars DataFrames don't plot themselves, but their expressive API makes pre-visualization data shaping trivial — which is where most chart mistakes originate. Before reaching for matplotlib or plotly, use `df.group_by().agg()` to pre-aggregate. Plotting raw granular data when you need summaries is the #1 source of chartjunk.

Chart selection starts with your column types. Use `df.schema` to inspect: temporal + numeric → line chart; categorical + numeric → bar chart; two numeric → scatter. Avoid pie charts for more than 4 categories — use `df.sort(col, descending=True).head(5)` to trim before plotting.

For color accessibility, extract your series count with `df.select(pl.col('category').n_unique()).item()` and choose a colorblind-safe palette sized accordingly (Okabe-Ito or IBM Design). Never rely on color alone — pair with markers or annotations.

Convert to pandas only at the plot boundary: `df.to_pandas()` keeps the heavy lifting in Polars' Rust engine. Use `cast(pl.Date)` before plotting to let matplotlib auto-format axes correctly rather than fighting string labels.$escape$,
  $escape$import polars as pl
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

df = pl.read_csv("metrics.csv")

# Pre-aggregate in Polars, not in the plotting layer
plot_df = (
    df.group_by("category")
    .agg(pl.col("value").mean().alias("avg_value"))
    .sort("avg_value", descending=True)
    .head(6)
)

# Colorblind-safe palette sized to actual series count
palette = ["#648FFF","#785EF0","#DC267F","#FE6100","#FFB000","#000000"]
pd_df = plot_df.to_pandas()
pd_df.plot.barh(x="category", y="avg_value", color=palette[:len(pd_df)])
plt.xlabel("Avg Value")
plt.tight_layout()
plt.savefig("chart.png", dpi=150)$escape$,
  $escape$python$escape$,
